<section xml:id="sec-cauchy-sequences">
  <title>Cauchy sequences</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Characterize sequences using the Cauchy condition and relate it to convergence.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use completeness of <m>\bb{R}</m> to conclude that Cauchy sequences converge.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove the Monotone Convergence Theorem.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        A sequence is a Cauchy sequence if for all <m>\eps>0</m> there exists some <m>N\in\bb N</m> such that <m>|a_{m}-a_{n}|&#x3C;\eps</m> for all <m>m,n>N</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If a sequence is Cauchy, then it is bounded.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If a sequence converges, then it is Cauchy.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If a sequence <em>in a complete space</em> is Cauchy, then it converges.
        This property is called Cauchy completeness.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\eps/2</m> trick
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        “Ratio test”: If <m>(a_{n})</m> is positive and <m>\limit{n\to\infty}\dfrac{a_{n+1}}{a_{n}}</m>, then <m>\limit{n\to\infty}a_{n}=0</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Monotone convergence theorem: A monotone sequence of real numbers converges if and only if it is bounded.
        Furthermore, the limit is the supremum or infimum.
        (Could apply to definition of <m>\ee</m>.)
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
